*  scan-talk-frame
** Pattern: Scan → Talk → Frame
   + CONTEXT:
     A practitioner has capabilities but no pipeline. The gap
     between "what I can do" and "who will pay for it" feels
     like an abyss. Fantasy fabrication fills the gap: "wouldn't
     it be nice to get paid for what I love doing."
   + IF:
     The practitioner has a systematic scan (probes), an agent
     to talk with (structured conversation), and a frame schema
     (what to record).
   + HOWEVER:
     Scanning alone produces data, not direction. Talking alone
     produces narrative, not structure. Recording alone produces
     archives, not momentum.
   + THEN:
     Combine all three into a daily hour: scan the landscape
     (5 min automated), talk through each item as a braindump
     (45 min), structure the output as a frame (10 min). The
     frame is the artifact. The conversation is the adapter.
     The scan is the stimulus.
   + BECAUSE:
     Fantasy dissolves when confronted with specifics. "Wouldn't
     it be nice" becomes "Logseq has $50K on OpenCollective and
     913 open tickets — do I want to close tickets or pitch a
     roadmap?" The pattern replaces vague aspiration with
     concrete assessment, repeated daily until the pipeline
     either materialises or the approach is revised.
   + NOTE:
     This is intentional saṃskāra — the deliberate fabrication
     of mental formations that serve the practitioner. The
     "unhelpful fabrication" is the dream of being paid for
     passion. The "helpful fabrication" is the daily discipline
     of scanning, assessing, and recording. Both are fabricated;
     one produces evidence, the other produces fantasy.
   + RELATED:
     - depositing/grant-to-pitch (same skill, different recipient)
     - war-machine/cardinal-directions (foraging → cargo → depositing)
     - nomadology/smooth-striated (scan navigates smooth space;
       frame striates it into actionable structure)
